WEBVTT

00:00.701 --> 00:08.741
                     ♪

00:08.743 --> 00:12.611
  bill: I swear that this game
     of crab fishing can be

00:12.613 --> 00:15.581
      the absolute biggest
    emotional roller coaster

00:15.583 --> 00:18.584
   of any job you'd ever have
      in your entire life.

00:18.586 --> 00:21.053
           -All right!
             -Yeah!

00:21.055 --> 00:23.889
           [ cheers ]

00:23.891 --> 00:26.425
              bill:
  Pot to pot, string to string,
           day to day.

00:26.427 --> 00:28.427
             -Whoa!
             -Yeah!

00:28.429 --> 00:30.629
    It's a good day at work.

00:30.631 --> 00:33.532
   Bill: You can have some of
  your best emotional highs...

00:33.534 --> 00:34.533
   [ chuckling ] it's packed!

00:34.535 --> 00:36.001
        Whoo!

00:39.707 --> 00:42.641
              Bill:
 ...And you can hit some bottoms
     you never knew you had.

00:44.011 --> 00:45.611
    What did the doctor say?

00:47.048 --> 00:48.447
            [ sighs ]

00:48.449 --> 00:51.383
           -look out!
            -Oh, no!

00:51.385 --> 00:53.619
 Oh, yeah, it's bad.

00:53.621 --> 00:57.456
        Bill: To do this,
       we have to endure.

00:57.458 --> 00:58.957
     Sean: This dude fought
        for our country.

00:58.959 --> 01:01.660
       He's gonna show us
     how tough he really is.

01:01.662 --> 01:04.396
     -There are no excuses.
              -Ow!

01:04.397 --> 01:07.132
I want to do my job.

01:07.134 --> 01:08.934
      If the job was easy,
     everybody would do it.

01:08.936 --> 01:11.036
             Are you kidding me?
                 I got this.

01:11.038 --> 01:12.304
               Ow!

01:12.306 --> 01:15.274
     --<font color="#ffff00"> Captions by vitac</font> --
         <font color="#00ffff"> www.Vitac.Com</font>

01:15.276 --> 01:18.310
      captions paid for by
    discovery communications

01:22.483 --> 01:26.085
            narrator:
    Just 132 miles northwest
       of dutch harbor...

01:30.424 --> 01:33.959
              Sig:
     Down south is a desert.

01:33.961 --> 01:38.130
   Everybody else went way up
      north, and we stayed.

01:38.132 --> 01:39.698
            Narrator:
   ...Left behind by the fleet

01:39.700 --> 01:43.635
    who headed north long ago
 to cash in on the russian line,

01:43.637 --> 01:47.806
  the <i> northwestern</i> patrols the
 southern opilio grounds alone.

01:50.411 --> 01:52.644
      Sig: I'm trying to be
       enthusiastic here.

01:52.646 --> 01:55.614
  We've had one of the roughest
      starts I can remember

01:55.616 --> 01:57.282
  for many different reasons --

01:57.284 --> 02:01.286
           mechanical,
      electrical, personal.

02:02.323 --> 02:04.022
          [ chuckles ]

02:04.024 --> 02:06.225
 need to see some crab here now.

02:06.227 --> 02:09.261
            Narrator:
   These southern waters have
   barely put a dent in sig's

02:09.263 --> 02:12.264
   $1.8 million opilio quota,

02:12.266 --> 02:15.400
     leaving him scrambling
      for any sign of life.

02:15.402 --> 02:16.301
         Sig: <i> You ready?</i>

02:16.303 --> 02:17.903
     <i> First pot's coming up.</i>

02:17.905 --> 02:23.242
                     ♪

02:23.244 --> 02:28.547
                     ♪

02:28.549 --> 02:31.717
    so, this is a tester pot
    we threw out last night.

02:31.719 --> 02:35.621
     It's got about 14 hours
          soaked on it.

02:35.623 --> 02:38.357
    If this thing hits crab,
            you know,

02:38.359 --> 02:40.025
         we just bought
        some real estate,

02:40.027 --> 02:42.261
         and that's what
  we're looking for right now.

02:45.900 --> 02:48.800
   Come on, come on, come on,
   come on, come on, come on.

02:51.705 --> 02:53.539
       Oh, no.

02:54.208 --> 02:56.175
               Aw.

02:57.478 --> 03:01.046
Narrator: Unfortunately for sig,
      there's a good reason

03:01.048 --> 03:03.482
        no one is fishing
       this close to town.

03:08.322 --> 03:11.557
   That -- that I don't like.

03:11.559 --> 03:14.393
                     ♪

03:19.733 --> 03:21.166
            [ sighs ]

03:21.168 --> 03:25.103
              yeah.

03:25.105 --> 03:27.673
         There's rumors
      of fishing up north,

03:27.675 --> 03:29.975
          and it looks
       real good up there.

03:29.977 --> 03:35.347
      But I have my reasons
      for being down here.

03:35.349 --> 03:37.583
            Narrator:
      Just two days ago...

03:37.585 --> 03:39.751
              Well,
      I can be there in --

03:39.753 --> 03:41.386
        in the next day.

03:41.388 --> 03:43.755
            Narrator:
   ...Sig received tragic news
           from June,

03:43.757 --> 03:46.858
      his wife and soulmate
          of 21 years.

03:46.860 --> 03:50.229
     It sounds like my wife
      has a form of cancer.

03:53.767 --> 03:56.668
             Mandy:
  So, right now, we're waiting
      for word to find out

03:56.670 --> 03:58.870
      how bad it really is.

03:58.872 --> 04:00.772
   We were planning on moving
       our gear up north.

04:00.774 --> 04:03.508
  We heard there's much better
        fishing up there.

04:03.510 --> 04:05.110
            However,
    because of the bad news,

04:05.112 --> 04:09.815
 I think it's best that we stay
  as close to land as possible.

04:09.817 --> 04:12.684
       Oh, no!

04:12.686 --> 04:14.853
    We got to put these pots
            on crab.

04:14.855 --> 04:16.521
   That's all there is to it.

04:18.225 --> 04:20.325
    It'll be a miserable day
          if we don't.

04:22.730 --> 04:25.564
         Sig: You know,
   these numbers are terrible.

04:25.566 --> 04:31.336
  But we're not going anywhere
  until I know how my wife is.

04:31.338 --> 04:33.939
       [ exhales sharply ]

04:33.941 --> 04:38.076
 she's always been there for me,

04:38.078 --> 04:41.113
  and I will be there for her.

04:41.115 --> 04:43.715
  Until I hear from the doctor,

04:43.717 --> 04:46.485
 stick and stay and make it pay.

04:46.487 --> 04:48.120
        That's our motto.

04:52.092 --> 04:56.561
            Narrator:
     396 miles northwest...

04:56.563 --> 04:59.231
              Sean:
    Well, long ways up here.

05:01.302 --> 05:03.735
            Narrator:
  ...The <i> brenna a</i> has arrived.

05:03.737 --> 05:05.070
              Sean:
   This is the furthest north

05:05.072 --> 05:09.341
      and the furthest west
        I have ever been.

05:09.343 --> 05:11.309
  Getting close to where I want
        to start setting.

05:11.311 --> 05:13.011
Hopefully there's a lot of crab.

05:13.013 --> 05:16.381
   Got some ground to make up.

05:16.383 --> 05:18.016
       Feeling optimistic.

05:22.756 --> 05:25.257
     Showed up kind of late
          to the party.

05:25.259 --> 05:27.692
    It's a nice big hot spot
            up here.

05:27.694 --> 05:30.829
  A lot of company, but that's
     generally what happens.

05:30.831 --> 05:34.399
 The biggest the pile of [bleep]
   the more flies you attract.

05:34.401 --> 05:37.402
  Narrator: After striking out
 down south, captain sean dwyer

05:37.404 --> 05:42.307
  elbows his way into the mosh
    pit of the russian line,

05:42.309 --> 05:46.578
       looking to party on
  the northern opilio grounds.

05:46.580 --> 05:50.782
    These boys got a long day
         ahead of them.

05:50.784 --> 05:53.985
   Let's see how they do here.

05:53.987 --> 05:58.490
            Narrator:
  Below deck, the crew gears up
       for the coming set,

05:58.492 --> 06:01.493
 eager to make up for lost crab.

06:01.495 --> 06:03.095
  Brandon: Living like I'm back
     in the military again,

06:03.097 --> 06:04.229
   so that's kind of exciting.

06:04.231 --> 06:07.399
         And, you know,
    got myself a little bunk,

06:07.401 --> 06:10.168
          get to put up
   the pictures of the family.

06:10.170 --> 06:11.670
         That's my life.
        They are my life.

06:11.672 --> 06:14.406
    That's what I'm here for.
    I do everything for them.

06:14.408 --> 06:16.508
            Narrator:
   The <i> brenna's</i> newest crewman
          is decorated

06:16.510 --> 06:21.413
   former marine and new hire,
    greenhorn brandon ferris.

06:21.415 --> 06:23.448
      Brandon: That's iraq.

06:23.450 --> 06:24.916
   Went there a couple times.

06:24.918 --> 06:27.619
     Echo 25 infantry, baby.

06:27.621 --> 06:29.187
 So I know what it's like to do
        all the gruntwork

06:29.189 --> 06:32.324
  and be a boot and a greenhorn
      all over again, so...

06:32.326 --> 06:33.825
   Anybody in the marine corps
         watching this,

06:33.827 --> 06:36.628
you know what I'm talking about.
   I'm a boot all over again.

06:36.630 --> 06:38.430
   I'm excited for it, though.
           I'm ready.

06:38.432 --> 06:41.032
 I'm grateful as hell that sean
    gave me this opportunity.

06:41.034 --> 06:43.001
  Here, it's kind of the same,
        like camaraderie.

06:43.003 --> 06:44.202
       I can already tell
        that's how it is.

06:44.204 --> 06:46.204
     You got a brotherhood.
          I like that.

06:46.206 --> 06:48.140
 So I just got to work and prove
             to sean

06:48.142 --> 06:51.109
     that I want to be here
         and stay here.

06:51.111 --> 06:55.046
 It's gonna hurt and be painful,
 but in the end, it's worth it.

06:57.551 --> 06:59.217
              Sean:
   Time to get her done, man.

07:00.454 --> 07:04.456
              Argh.
   Ready to plunder the deep?

07:04.458 --> 07:06.691
       Roger!
    We're ready.

07:11.265 --> 07:13.265
          [ chuckles ]

07:13.267 --> 07:18.937
                     ♪

07:18.939 --> 07:20.405
        whoo!

07:20.407 --> 07:23.375
           Off we go.
           Back at it.

07:23.377 --> 07:28.313
                     ♪

07:28.315 --> 07:29.915
        whoo!

07:29.917 --> 07:32.384
    So, hopefully, we can get
     these things dialed in.

07:34.154 --> 07:37.189
                     ♪

07:37.191 --> 07:38.924
            narrator:
   Just up the russian line...

07:42.162 --> 07:43.628
              Josh:
   The north is a crazy place.

07:43.630 --> 07:47.499
     It's vast and desolate.

07:49.069 --> 07:53.805
   There ain't nothing up here
        except for crab.

07:54.975 --> 07:58.143
Man: Let's get it, boys!
  Get me some crab!

07:59.713 --> 08:03.315
 ...The <i> cornelia marie</i> continues
    to bomb the russian line.

08:03.317 --> 08:10.622
                     ♪

08:13.994 --> 08:15.393
              josh:
 After getting our asses kicked

08:15.395 --> 08:17.496
      like ronda rousey did
         twice in a row.

08:17.498 --> 08:20.665
   We feel like the flag looks
            up there.

08:20.667 --> 08:22.567
            Narrator:
  After taking every last blow

08:22.569 --> 08:24.903
     that arctic storm elsa
         could muster...

08:24.905 --> 08:26.738
       Beeeep!
            [ beep ]

08:28.542 --> 08:31.309
   ...Co-captains josh harris
        and casey mcmanus

08:31.311 --> 08:34.379
  are still standing and still
       dead set on nailing

08:34.381 --> 08:38.717
their $1.23 million opilio quota
        in a single trip.

08:38.719 --> 08:40.818
Josh: I'm telling you, man,
we're the perfect combination

08:40.821 --> 08:42.554
 of lucky and good.

08:42.556 --> 08:44.656
  Well, now we're gonna find out
               if we're good,

08:44.658 --> 08:46.157
               if we can stay
               on top of them.

08:49.463 --> 08:50.929
        Whoo!

08:53.400 --> 08:55.767
    Josh: The guys are beaten
          and battered,

08:55.769 --> 08:58.803
      but I'm pushing them
           to the max.

08:58.805 --> 09:01.773
       We all love money.
     They'll thank me later,

09:01.775 --> 09:03.909
       because we're gonna
       fill this puppy up.

09:03.911 --> 09:06.711
             -Good!
    -We got three more to go.

09:06.713 --> 09:09.214
      Man: Hey!
Okay, let's go, let's go.

09:11.251 --> 09:12.918
            Jon: Ow!

09:17.524 --> 09:20.258
           [ groans ]

09:20.260 --> 09:22.427
         say that again?

09:22.429 --> 09:24.563
  You all right there, big dog?

09:24.565 --> 09:26.197
     Jon: Oh...

09:28.735 --> 09:30.669
      Got my hand smashed.
   I'm kind of shaking it off,

09:30.671 --> 09:33.104
  but let's take the glove off
      and see what we got,

09:33.106 --> 09:35.473
    'cause it [bleep] hurts.

09:40.247 --> 09:42.380
       Oh, yeah, it's bad.

09:42.382 --> 09:45.517
      Oh, it's [bleep] bad.

09:45.519 --> 09:48.253
  Like my dad says,
don't put your finger

09:48.255 --> 09:50.155
 where you wouldn't
   put your penis.

09:50.157 --> 09:53.758
             Oh. Oh.

09:53.760 --> 09:55.594
              Ooh.

09:55.596 --> 09:57.462
     We got to go see casey
          on this one.

10:00.133 --> 10:02.133
Casey: What the [bleep]
  happened to you?

10:02.135 --> 10:03.668
      I may or may not have
          put my finger

10:03.670 --> 10:06.104
   in a compromised situation
         during the set.

10:10.677 --> 10:12.310
               Oh.

10:15.282 --> 10:18.883
            Narrator:
     As the boat shifts, the
 800-pound pot slides starboard,

10:18.885 --> 10:21.853
        crushing engineer
   jon farrell's middle finger

10:21.855 --> 10:24.222
      between the crossbar
          and the rail,

10:24.224 --> 10:27.425
   resulting in a blunt-force
     impact powerful enough

10:27.427 --> 10:32.497
     to lacerate the finger
        down to the bone.

10:32.499 --> 10:35.367
        Whoa,
  that's meat, dog.

10:35.369 --> 10:39.437
     Or, in technical terms,
 he smashed the crap out of it.

10:39.439 --> 10:42.107
           -Facebook.
            -No. Aah!

10:42.109 --> 10:44.876
      -That needs sutures.
          -Oh, I know.

10:44.878 --> 10:46.244
      Come on.

10:46.246 --> 10:48.980
Let's stitch this bitch up
so I don't lose you on deck.

10:55.822 --> 10:57.088
              Casey: Lidocaine.

10:57.090 --> 10:58.623
                   Bingo!

10:58.625 --> 11:01.359
     Should we give him the good
     stuff or the expired stuff?

11:01.361 --> 11:02.961
            Narrator:
 In a rare moment of compassion,

11:02.963 --> 11:06.464
    casey will numb the wound
    with a local anesthetic.

11:06.466 --> 11:09.367
   But he'll still get to jab
        the bone-deep cut

11:09.369 --> 11:11.803
      with a 3-inch needle.

11:11.805 --> 11:15.807
     I always wanted to do that.
  I seen that done on a tv show.

11:15.809 --> 11:19.444
              God, I'm shaking
                like a leaf.

11:19.446 --> 11:21.579
       I'm getting nervous
   letting casey do this now.

11:21.581 --> 11:23.481
   It's okay, bud.
  I'm here for you.

11:23.483 --> 11:24.616
             Are you kidding me?

11:24.618 --> 11:26.651
                 I got this.

11:26.653 --> 11:28.219
                 I'll fix it
        like I'm a professional.

11:28.221 --> 11:30.955
                  Trust me.

11:30.957 --> 11:32.223
                 All right.

11:32.225 --> 11:35.193
             Little, tiny poke.

11:35.195 --> 11:38.329
                 Don't move
                your finger.

11:38.331 --> 11:39.597
              Aah!

11:39.599 --> 11:41.332
            Damn it!

11:48.375 --> 11:49.941
            Jon: Aah!

11:49.943 --> 11:54.345
    Narrator: 229 miles from
      the nearest medic...

11:54.347 --> 11:56.314
                   Casey:
         Don't move your finger.

11:56.316 --> 11:58.883
         Aah, you bitch!

11:58.885 --> 12:00.218
            Narrator:
    ...Captain casey prepares

12:00.220 --> 12:03.354
       to perform surgery
     on the galley table...

12:04.624 --> 12:07.959
              -Ow!
    -...Which is good or bad,

12:07.961 --> 12:11.563
      depending on whether
  you're a patient or a diner.

12:11.565 --> 12:14.065
          Jon: Ow! Oh!

12:14.067 --> 12:15.133
              Aah!

12:15.135 --> 12:17.135
            That was a good one.

12:17.137 --> 12:18.203
               Mm.

12:18.205 --> 12:19.537
            -Scalpel.
            -Scalpel.

12:26.046 --> 12:27.645
              -Ow!
         -Whoa, oh, oh.

12:27.647 --> 12:30.181
           Jon: Sorry.

12:30.183 --> 12:31.316
              That's your skin.

12:31.318 --> 12:33.384
              -Aw.
              -Ew.

12:33.386 --> 12:34.686
Okay, you guys go away.

12:34.688 --> 12:36.387
     Seriously,
you're making me nervous.

12:37.357 --> 12:39.557
               Got to youtube
       how to do stitches again.

12:39.559 --> 12:41.860
           [ laughing ] hang on.

12:43.830 --> 12:44.963
                 You ready?

12:44.965 --> 12:46.531
        Yeah.

12:46.533 --> 12:48.833
     Getting a fairly good chunk
                of the meat.

12:48.835 --> 12:51.136
           Let's make our suture
               close properly.

12:54.674 --> 12:58.109
               Loop, through,
                  and pull.

12:58.111 --> 13:00.044
          Hey, I got it through.

13:00.046 --> 13:01.980
  Congratulations.

13:04.251 --> 13:06.284
                    Boom.
                 Nailed it.

13:08.655 --> 13:10.989
 Narrator: Nine stitches later,
         farrell is back

13:10.991 --> 13:13.491
       to full strength --
            mostly...

13:13.493 --> 13:15.660
Casey did a pretty good job
  stitching me up.

13:15.662 --> 13:17.729
      It's what
my best friend does.

13:17.731 --> 13:20.198
   I fix his boat,
he fixes my fingers.

13:20.200 --> 13:22.066
           ...Meaning
       the <i> cornelia marie</i>

13:22.068 --> 13:25.470
     can get back to fishing
   after a quick bite to eat.

13:25.472 --> 13:27.839
         -Oh, it's cold.
      -Want me to nuke it?

13:27.841 --> 13:32.010
    Yeah, please.
   I'm so hungry.

13:32.012 --> 13:34.145
That's all I was looking forward
to doing was eating,

13:34.147 --> 13:36.114
      and then
I smashed my finger.

13:36.116 --> 13:42.120
                     ♪

13:42.122 --> 13:45.757
   narrator: 389 miles away...

13:45.759 --> 13:48.092
                  Oh, man.

13:48.094 --> 13:50.295
         [ speaks indistinctly ]

13:50.297 --> 13:54.165
    ...In the nearly deserted
   southern opilio grounds...

13:54.167 --> 14:00.038
   This area's really, really
      wrecking havoc on us.

14:00.040 --> 14:04.509
   These numbers are terrible,
   and it's not what we want.

14:04.511 --> 14:05.877
   But we don't have a choice.

14:05.879 --> 14:10.081
    We're not going anywhere
  until I know how my wife is.

14:10.083 --> 14:12.550
 Narrator: ...Captain sig hansen
    and the <i> northwestern</i> crew

14:12.552 --> 14:14.619
            scrape up
   what little they can find,

14:14.621 --> 14:18.690
      staying close to land
   and a possible flight out.

14:18.692 --> 14:21.860
      This cancer business
    has been driving me nuts.

14:24.331 --> 14:25.864
                     Oh!

14:28.134 --> 14:31.035
           Oh, my god.
    I just [bleep] hate this.

14:33.273 --> 14:36.074
      [ telephone ringing ]

14:36.076 --> 14:37.542
            oh, heya.

14:37.544 --> 14:39.077
     June: Heya.

14:39.079 --> 14:42.347
         Hey, did you --
      did you go in today?

14:45.585 --> 14:47.285
    What did the doctor say?

14:54.261 --> 14:57.896
  So nothing spread and there's
  no more that they could find?

14:57.898 --> 15:00.531
          You're sure?
       You are 100% sure?

15:02.202 --> 15:04.669
          [ chuckles ]

15:04.671 --> 15:06.137
       that's great news.

15:06.139 --> 15:08.406
  Either way, I can come home.

15:08.408 --> 15:10.275
         Snap a finger,
        and I'll be down.

15:18.318 --> 15:21.152
              Yeah.

15:21.154 --> 15:22.687
              Okay.

15:22.689 --> 15:23.755
      All right, love you.

15:23.757 --> 15:24.989
    I'll get off this thing.

15:24.991 --> 15:26.524
        Okay.

15:29.930 --> 15:33.097
          I will. Okay.
            Love you.

15:33.099 --> 15:36.200
               Ah.

15:36.202 --> 15:38.903
   Well, that's a damn relief.

15:38.905 --> 15:42.507
        And she's right.

15:42.509 --> 15:45.643
    It's like everybody else
   is counting on this season,

15:45.645 --> 15:47.912
            so yeah.

15:47.914 --> 15:51.049
     I needed to hear that.

15:51.051 --> 15:53.017
    Narrator: With good news
       on the homefront...

15:53.019 --> 15:56.521
              Sig:
 We might as well go to where we
 think there's stronger fishing,

15:56.523 --> 15:58.089
      and that's up north.

15:58.091 --> 16:02.160
            Narrator:
  ...Sig turns his bow and his
   focus to the russian line.

16:02.162 --> 16:03.661
              Sig:
 <i> We're gonna make a move here.</i>

16:03.663 --> 16:06.597
